Question:Find and print the largest number.
Input:
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(11, 7, 19, 3);

Solution:-
Java 8 Streams find the maximum using the max(Comparator) terminal operation on a stream of Integer values. For input [11, 7, 19, 3], it prints 19.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list via stream(). 
Call max(Comparator.naturalOrder()) to get Optional<Integer> with largest by natural order. 
Use ifPresent(System.out::println) to print if present.
​
#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Comparator;
import java.util.List;

public class FindMaxPrint {
    public static void findAndPrintMax(List<Integer> numbers) {
        numbers.stream()
               .max(Comparator.naturalOrder())
               .ifPresent(System.out::println);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(11, 7, 19, 3);
        findAndPrintMax(list);
    }
}

Prints 19. Optional.ifPresent handles safely without .get() NPE risk.
​
#Thought Process
max(comparator) reduces stream to largest via comparisons. Natural order ascending for Integer. Returns Optional for empty safety. Alternatives like reduce(Integer::max) or mapToInt().max() possible; max clearest for single max.
​
#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty Optional, nothing prints (no NPE).​
Null list: NPE on stream(); null-check.
Null elements: NPE if null compared; filter Objects::nonNull first.​
Single element: Returns that element.
All equals: Returns any (first stable).
Negatives/large: Handles INT_MIN/MAX fine.
